          "body": "Lot 'lifted up his eyes' (nasa, 13:10) and surveyed the Jordan valley. The description of what he saw is stunning: 'well watered everywhere — like the garden of the LORD, like the land of Egypt' (13:10). Two supreme landscapes of abundance collapse into one image. Lot's choice, by every visible criterion, is impeccable. The problem is the narrator's parenthesis: this was before the LORD destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah (13:10), and — in case the reader has not yet understood — 'the men of Sodom were wicked exceedingly and sinners against the LORD' (13:13). Lot sees a paradise; the narrator sees a condemned city. Lot chooses by appearance; the text evaluates by holiness. The eastward direction compounds the irony: *qedem* (east) in Genesis is consistently the direction of departure from God's presence. Cain went east after his curse (4:16); Babel's builders came from the east (11:2); now Lot journeys eastward (13:11). What begins as a move toward maximum prosperity becomes, by incremental steps, a drift into Sodom's orbit — and eventually its gates (14:12; 19:1). As Keller has noted, Lot's tragedy is not a dramatic apostasy but a series of small choices toward comfort that compound into catastrophe."
