          "body": "The chapter closes not with a land survey or a legal document but with an altar: 'he built an altar to the LORD' (13:18). Abram settles at the oaks of Mamre near Hebron and immediately worships. This is the patriarchal pattern without deviation — every significant divine encounter in Genesis 12-22 is answered with altar-building (12:7, 8; 13:4, 18; 22:9). The altar at Hebron is more than a religious gesture. Hebron will become the first soil Abram legally owns in Canaan (the cave of Machpelah, purchased in Gen. 23 for Sarah's burial). The altar anticipates the possession; the worship precedes the legal title. For the author of Hebrews, this entire pattern makes sense only eschatologically: Abram 'was looking for the city which has foundations, whose architect and builder is God' (Hebrews 11:10). The tent-dwelling, the altar-building, the refusal to seize what God has promised to give — all of it expresses a faith that knows the ultimate land is not mapped by human surveys. Genesis 13 ends as it began: Abram at an altar, calling on the name of the LORD."
