        "number": 1,
        "title": "Returning to the altar — worship as the precondition of everything that follows",
        "range": "13:1-4",
        "excerpt": "He went on his journeys from the Negev as far as Bethel, to the place where his tent had been at the beginning... and there Abram called on the name of the LORD.",
        "body": "Genesis 13 opens with Abram's deliberate geographical reversal. He has been expelled from Egypt — enriched, but humiliated, his deception exposed, his covenant testimony damaged. The narrative of 12:10-20 is one of faith's failures: Abram left the promised land under pressure, lied about his wife to protect himself, and was corrected not by God's people but by Pharaoh. Genesis 13 is the narrative of return. Abram retraces his exact prior route, stopping at each former campsite, until he reaches Bethel — 'the place where his tent had been at the beginning' (13:3). The Hebrew *techillah* (beginning, formerly) is deliberate. Abram is not exploring new territory; he is recovering lost ground.\n\nThe chapter's opening act is worship: at the altar he had made 'there formerly,' Abram calls on the name of Yahweh (13:4). This is the same act described at the altar's original construction in 12:8, using the same verb (*qara*, to call, to invoke). What had been interrupted by the Egyptian detour is now resumed. Calvin's comment on this verse is precise: Abram's return to the altar was his public confession that the Egyptian journey had been a deviation, and that his true standing before God was not as a wealthy returnee from Egypt but as a covenant-traveler to the land of promise.\n\nThe significance for the chapter's structure cannot be overstated. Everything that follows — Abram's generous offer to Lot, his trust that allows him to yield the first choice, his reception of the expanded covenant promise — is grounded in this restored posture of worship. The altar is not a spiritual footnote; it is the epistemological foundation. A man who has called on Yahweh's name at an altar has reestablished his frame of reference. He knows who owns the land; he knows who has promised; he knows that his portion is not at risk because it is not in human hands. The conflicts of verses 5-13 are navigated by a man who has just been at the altar. That sequence is not incidental.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qara beshel YHWH* — 'called on the name of the LORD' — is the standard patriarchal phrase for public, covenantal worship (cf. 12:8; 21:33; 26:25). It denotes more than private prayer; it is an invocation that claims the covenant relationship. *Techillah* (formerly, at first) appears only twice in Genesis 13 (vv. 3, 4) and marks Abram's intentional return to the original covenant-geography."
