        "excerpt": "Please let there be no strife between you and me... Is not the whole land before you? Please separate from me.",
        "body": "The conflict between herdsmen (13:6-7) is a property dispute, but the narrator frames it with a theologically charged observation: 'the Canaanite and the Perizzite were dwelling then in the land' (13:7). This parenthesis is not background color; it is a moral alarm. The nations whose land the covenant community is to inhabit are watching. The strife of Abram's and Lot's servants is a public testimony — and at this moment, a damaging one. Abram's response to the conflict must therefore be read on two levels: as pastoral wisdom and as covenant witness before the watching Canaanites.\n\nAbram's offer to Lot is remarkable in its specificity. He does not propose arbitration, joint management, or territorial compromise. He gives Lot the entire choice: 'If to the left, then I will go to the right; or if to the right, then I will go to the left' (13:9). By ancient Near Eastern custom, the elder and the covenant-bearer — and Abram is both — held priority of selection. His surrender of that right is not social generosity; it is theological confidence. The only basis for such an offer is the conviction that God's promise covers whatever portion remains. A man uncertain of his inheritance guards it; a man confident of it can release it.\n\nSwindoll has noted that Abram's offer is one of the clearest early examples of the principle Paul will articulate in Philippians 2:3: 'Do nothing from selfishness or empty conceit, but with humility of mind regard one another as more important than yourselves.' But in Abram's case, the humility is not mere virtue — it is eschatological. He yields to Lot because God has spoken. The promise in 12:7 ('to your descendants I will give this land') means that the land's ultimate disposition is not Abram's to negotiate. He can release the choice precisely because it has already been decided.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Na* (please, 13:8, 9) is the Hebrew particle of urgent entreaty — Abram is not commanding Lot but beseeching him. The word appears twice in Abram's speech, conveying the depth of his desire to preserve family unity. *Ach* (13:8, brothers/kinsmen) — Abram grounds his appeal in the covenant-family bond. The word encompasses both biological kinship and the shared identity of those who travel together under the covenant."
