        "body": "The narrator describes Lot's decision-making process with surgical precision: he 'lifted up his eyes and saw' (13:10). The landscape he surveys is unambiguously beautiful — 'well watered everywhere,' described with the two greatest landscape archetypes available to the biblical imagination: 'like the garden of the LORD' (Eden, Genesis 2:10-14) and 'like the land of Egypt' (the Nile Delta, the ancient world's breadbasket). Lot's choice, by every visible criterion, is rational, even shrewd. He maximizes his economic position and secures abundant resources for his herds.\n\nThe narrator's parenthetical comment in verse 10 — 'this was before the LORD destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah' — is one of the most devastating literary moves in the patriarchal narratives. It inserts the end of the story into the middle of the choice, forcing the reader to evaluate what Lot sees with information Lot does not have. The Jordan valley, described as paradise, is on a countdown to annihilation. The garden-like plain will become, by Genesis 19, a landscape of ash and sulfur. Lot is choosing his paradise on borrowed time.\n\nVerse 13 is the narrator's editorial verdict: 'the men of Sodom were wicked exceedingly and sinners against the LORD.' The double intensifier (*ra meod*, wicked exceedingly) is the same construction used of the pre-flood generation (6:5) and of Pharaoh's repeated heart-hardening in Exodus. The sin of Sodom is not merely civic disorder; it is specifically *against the LORD* — a vertical, covenantal transgression. Lot is pitching his tent in the orbit of a city whose wickedness the narrator qualifies with the gravest possible language. What began as an eastward journey ends with the tents moved 'as far as Sodom' (13:12). The word *ad* (as far as) marks the outer edge of a drift that has not yet stopped. By 14:12, Lot is living inside Sodom; by 19:1, he is sitting in its gate.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kikkar* (plain, disk, 13:10-12) — the Jordan disk or circle, the visible disc of the valley floor. The word is used five times in this chapter for the Jordan valley, always in contexts that mark it as Lot's chosen domain. *Qedem* (east, 13:11) — in Genesis, the direction of exile: Eden's eastern gate (3:24), Cain's eastward wandering (4:16), Babel's eastern origin (11:2). Lot's eastward journey is narratively coded as a departure from the promise-land trajectory."
